## Step B — CASE WHEN with Math: Per-Subscription Monthly Rate

**Concept:** CASE WHEN can wrap an arithmetic expression, not just a
label. Annual subscriptions store the *full-year* price, so you divide
by 12 to get the monthly equivalent. Monthly subscriptions need no
adjustment.

**The MRR formula:**

```
Monthly sub:  seats × price_per_seat × (1 - discount_percent / 100.0)
Annual sub:   seats × price_per_seat × (1 - discount_percent / 100.0) / 12
```

The only difference is `/ 12` at the end of the Annual branch. Everything
else is identical.

**Your query:** Pull every active subscription with its calculated MRR.

**Return:** `subscription_id`, `plan_name`, `billing_cycle`, `seats`,
`price_per_seat`, `discount_percent`, `mrr` (rounded to 2 decimal places)

**Sort:** `mrr` descending

```sql
-- Step B: CASE WHEN with arithmetic
SELECT
    subscription_id,
    plan_name,
    billing_cycle,
    seats,
    price_per_seat,
    discount_percent,
    ROUND(
        CASE
            WHEN billing_cycle = 'Annual'
                THEN seats * price_per_seat * (1 - discount_percent / 100.0) / 12
            ELSE
                 seats * price_per_seat * (1 - discount_percent / 100.0)
        END
    , 2) AS mrr
FROM subscriptions
WHERE status = 'active'
ORDER BY mrr DESC;
```

**Self-check:** 49 rows. Top row: `SUB025` | Analytics Enterprise | Annual | `$6,840.00`.
Sum of the `mrr` column = **$142,110.50**.

> This is Q1 from the MRR Snapshot assignment — you already built this.
> The point of running it again here is to read the CASE WHEN structure
> clearly before it goes inside a SUM().

